<h2>Origins & History</h2>

<p>Prosecco's story begins in the rolling hills of northeastern Italy, where the <strong>Glera grape</strong> (formerly known as Prosecco) has been cultivated for over a millennium. The variety originated in the village of Prosecco, near Trieste, where Roman writers like Pliny the Elder documented a wine called "Pucinum" as early as the first century CE—believed by many scholars to be an early ancestor of today's Prosecco.</p>

<p>The modern understanding of Glera's genetic makeup reveals fascinating parentage connections. Recent DNA analysis has linked Glera to other northeastern Italian varieties, suggesting a complex web of natural crossings that occurred over centuries in the Veneto and Friuli regions. This grape thrived in the unique terroir of steep hillsides and mineral-rich soils, developing the high acidity and delicate floral characteristics that define quality Prosecco today.</p>

<h3>The Rise to Global Recognition</h3>

<p>While Glera remained largely regional until the 20th century, several key moments transformed it into an international phenomenon. The <strong>development of the Charmat method</strong> in the early 1900s revolutionized production, allowing winemakers to preserve Glera's fresh fruit character while creating consistent, affordable sparkling wine. The establishment of the Prosecco DOC in 1969, followed by the prestigious DOCG classifications for Conegliano Valdobbiadene and Asolo in 2009, elevated the wine's status dramatically.</p>

<p>The name "Prosecco" itself underwent significant change in 2009 when EU regulations reserved the term exclusively for wines from designated Italian regions, forcing the grape to be renamed Glera. This protected designation sparked a global planting boom, with <strong>over 25,000 hectares</strong> now under vine in the traditional zones alone.</p>

<h3>Global Expansion and Modern Trends</h3>

<p>Today, while authentic Prosecco remains tied to its Italian origins, Glera plantings have expanded worldwide. Australia, Argentina, and parts of California now cultivate the variety, though these wines cannot legally use the Prosecco name. The variety's adaptability to different climates, combined with growing consumer demand for accessible sparkling wines, has made it one of the fastest-growing wine categories globally, with production increasing over 300% in the past two decades.</p>

