<h2>Aging & Cellaring</h2>

<p>Unlike many still wines, prosecco's aging potential varies dramatically based on production method and quality tier. Understanding these differences is crucial for maximizing your investment in different prosecco options.</p>

<h3>Aging Potential by Style</h3>
<p><strong>Prosecco DOC</strong> (tank method): Best consumed within 1-2 years of vintage. The fresh, primary fruit flavors—green apple, pear, and citrus—begin to fade after 18 months, with the signature effervescence losing its vivacity.</p>

<p><strong>Prosecco DOCG Superiore</strong>: Can develop beautifully for 3-5 years when properly stored. Valdobbiadene and Conegliano examples gain honeyed complexity while maintaining their mineral backbone from the steep hillside soils.</p>

<p><strong>Metodo Classico Prosecco</strong>: The rare bottle-fermented versions can age 5-8 years, developing brioche, almond, and nutty autolysis characters similar to Champagne, though retaining prosecco's distinctive glera grape profile.</p>

<h3>Evolution Over Time</h3>
<p>Prosecco doesn't follow traditional wine aging patterns. Rather than tannin integration (glera has minimal tannins), you'll notice fruit evolution from bright primary flavors to more honeyed, dried fruit notes. The perlage becomes finer but less vigorous, and the wine's natural acidity provides the structure for graceful aging in premium examples.</p>

<h3>Proper Storage</h3>
<p>Store bottles horizontally at 50-55°F with 70% humidity in a dark environment. Unlike still wines, prosecco's cork allows minimal oxygen exchange, making temperature stability more critical than for wines with traditional corks.</p>

<h3>Quality Indicators</h3>
<p>Properly aged prosecco maintains bright acidity with evolved fruit complexity. Warning signs include browning color, flat effervescence, or oxidized aromas reminiscent of bruised apples. Premium DOCG examples should show golden hues and integrated bubbles when properly cellared, while basic DOC proseccos simply lose their youthful charm rather than gaining complexity.</p>

