    <p class="text-gray-700">High-quality DOCG Prosecco maintains effervescence and flavor for 2-3 days when properly resealed and refrigerated, thanks to finer bubbles and higher acidity. Standard DOC Prosecco typically loses its sparkle within 24 hours due to larger bubbles and lower pressure. Using a proper sparkling wine stopper rather than a regular cork extends freshness by 12-24 hours for any style.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">What are the biggest mistakes when choosing Prosecco for special events?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">The most common error is selecting the wrong sweetness level—many choose Demi-Sec thinking it's drier when Extra Dry is actually the crowd-pleasing middle ground. Another mistake is buying too far in advance; Prosecco should be consumed within 1-2 years of release for optimal freshness. Finally, people often overlook serving vessel—flute glasses concentrate aromas better than coupes for most Prosecco styles.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-wine-700 mb-2">When should I choose Franciacorta or Cava instead of Prosecco?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Choose Franciacorta when you want Champagne-style complexity and aging potential for formal occasions—its traditional method produces more sophisticated bubbles and flavors. Cava offers better value for large gatherings where you need sparkling wine with food-pairing versatility, especially with Spanish or Mediterranean cuisine. Stick with Prosecco for casual celebrations, aperitifs, or when you prefer fresh, fruit-forward flavors over yeasty, bread-like complexity.</p>
  </div>

  <div>
    <h3 class="text-lg font-semibeland text-wine-700 mb-2">How do organic and biodynamic Prosecco options compare to conventional ones?</h3>
    <p class="text-gray-700">Organic Prosecco producers like Ca' dei Zago and Astoria often show more pronounced minerality and terroir expression, though at a 20-30% price premium. Biodynamic versions from producers like Perlage exhibit exceptional purity but limited availability outside specialty wine shops. The flavor differences are subtle—conventional Prosecco can be equally delicious, making organic/biodynamic choices more about personal values than dramatic taste improvements.</p>
